    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-05-16T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-05-16T07:00:00-05:00" n="294"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d294">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">651.116 Nitrate/16: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Edge</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-05-16T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 16, 1931—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 16—10:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>261. Your 200, May 12, 6 p.m. I am advised by Acting Commercial Attaché that the
                    decree referred to was issued May 7. For details <pb facs="0379" n="259"
                        xml:id="pg_259"/> and text see Acting Commercial Attaché’s cables to his
                    Department numbers 256, 260, and 261.<note n="39" xml:id="d294fn39">No copies
                        found in Department files.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Mr. Reagan has the assurance of Minister of Agriculture that there will be
                    absolutely no discrimination. I assume therefore that if the Barrett Company
                    apply along the lines detailed Commercial Attaché’s cable No. 260 they will be
                    given every opportunity to continue in the market.</p>
                <p>There is no indication that the measure is aimed at American imports but is
                    designed to give the French a stronger hand in nitrogen negotiations now under
                    way in Paris.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Edge</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
